                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="35466" author="luke" created="Tue, 6 May 2008 23:53:37 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Good point. I guess we could skip values that start with a $. Otherwise, the checks will have to be moved into a post processor which runs after the configurer.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="35467" author="lucker" created="Tue, 6 May 2008 23:59:12 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;i think the second choose is preffered.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="35468" author="luke" created="Wed, 7 May 2008 00:08:13 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Actually, the checks can probably be moved into the actual beans themselves as they apply generally. That will be much simpler. I&apos;ve spent too much time working with bean parsers recently &lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://jira.spring.io/images/icons/emoticons/smile.png&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="35469" author="luke" created="Wed, 7 May 2008 00:53:12 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;After further consideration, I&apos;ve gone for an approach that checks both at parsing time (gives a warning rather than an error and ignores potential placeholders) and in the actual beans (using Assert calls). That way we don&apos;t lose the benefits of tooling but an error will still be raised if the values are wrong.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="126832" author="issuemaster" created="Sat, 6 Feb 2016 06:37:00 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This issue has been migrated to &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-security/issues/1078&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-security/issues/1078&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
